questiontext.text:
The waiting time (in minutes) at the cashier of two supermarketchains with different cashier systems is compared. The following statistical test was performed:

Two Sample t-test 

data:  Waiting by Supermarket
t = 2.5046, df = 126, p-value = 0.9932
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
95 percent confidence interval:
     -Inf 2.437739
sample estimates:
 mean in group Sparag mean in group Consumo 
             4.866842              3.399739

Which of the following statements are correct? (Significance level \(5\%\))

partiallycorrectfeedback.text:
• True. The absolute value of the test statistic is equal to \(2.505\).
  • True. The test aims at showing that the difference of means is  smaller than \(0\).
  • True. The \(p\)~value is equal to \(0.993\).
  • False. The test aims at showing that the alternative that the waiting time is shorter at Sparag than at Consumo. The test result is not significant (\(p \ge 0.05\)).
  • False.  The test result ist not significant (\(p \ge 0.05\)).

incorrectfeedback.text:
• True. The absolute value of the test statistic is equal to \(2.505\).
  • True. The test aims at showing that the difference of means is  smaller than \(0\).
  • True. The \(p\)~value is equal to \(0.993\).
  • False. The test aims at showing that the alternative that the waiting time is shorter at Sparag than at Consumo. The test result is not significant (\(p \ge 0.05\)).
  • False.  The test result ist not significant (\(p \ge 0.05\)).

answer.text: The absolute value of the test statistic is larger than \(1.96\).
The test shows that the waiting time is longer at Sparag  than at Consumo.
The test shows that the waiting time is shorter at Sparag than at Consumo.

questiontext.text: What is the derivative of \(f(x) = x^{7} e^{3.2x}\), evaluated at \(x = 0.67\)?

generalfeedback.text:
Using the product rule for \(f(x) = g(x) \cdot h(x)\), where \(g(x) := x^{7}\) and \(h(x) := e^{3.2x}\), we obtain
\begin{eqnarray*}
f'(x) & = & [g(x) \cdot h(x)]' = g'(x) \cdot h(x) + g(x) \cdot h'(x) \\
      & = & 7 x^{7 - 1} \cdot e^{3.2x} + x^{7} \cdot e^{3.2x} \cdot 3.2 \\
      & = & e^{3.2x} \cdot(7 x^6 + 3.2 x^{7}) \\
      & = & e^{3.2x} \cdot x^6 \cdot (7 + 3.2x).
\end{eqnarray*}
Evaluated at \(x = 0.67\), the answer is
\[ e^{3.2\cdot 0.67} \cdot 0.67^6 \cdot (7 + 3.2\cdot 0.67) = 7.0585. \]
Thus, rounded to two digits we have \(f'(0.67) = 7.06\).

questiontext.text: What is the distance between the two points \(p = (3, 2)\) and \(q = (5, 3)\) in a Cartesian coordinate system?

generalfeedback.text:
The distance \(d\) of \(p\) and \(q\) is given by \(d^2 = (p_1 - q_1)^2 + (p_2 - q_2)^2\) (Pythagorean formula).

Hence \(d = \sqrt{(p_1 - q_1)^2 + (p_2 - q_2)^2} = \sqrt{(3 - 5)^2 + (2 - 3)^2} = 2.236\).

questiontext.text: Using the data provided in regression.csv estimate a linear regression of \(\texttt{y}\) on \(\texttt{x}\). Estimated slope with respect to \(\texttt{x}\).

generalfeedback.text:
To replicate the analysis in R:

## data
d <- read.csv("regression.csv")
## regression
m <- lm(y ~ x, data = d)
summary(m)
## visualization
plot(y ~ x, data = d)
abline(m)

questiontext.text: What is the name of the R function for negative binomial regression?
